: A Comparison of the Dangers of Hormone Replacement Therapies in Profit versus National Health Care Delivery Systems -- t17. Women’s Health and Cardiovascular Care: A Persistent Divide -- t18. From Global to Local and Over the Rainbow: Violence Against Women -- t19. Women’s Access to Maternity Services in Canada: Historical Developments and Contemporary Challenges -- t20. Relocating Care: Home Care in Ontario -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, healthcare professionals have recognized the distinctly different healthcare needs and concerns of men and women. Women's health, in particular, has come into its own in the last two decades. In Canada, however, there has been little available in the way of a general text on women's health. This volume works toward filling that gap by providing a resource for teaching and understanding women's health in this country. To lay out the methodological and theoretical foundations for their study, editors Olena Hankivisky, Marina Morrow, and Colleen Varcoe bring together an interdisciplinary group of scholars and practitioners from economics, anthropology, sociology, nursing, political studies, women's studies, and psychology. Contributors draw on the rich history of the Canadian women's health movement, providing analysis of that history and of the emergent theory, policy, and practice. Aimed at undergraduate and graduate students as well as practitioners, the collection adopts an intersectional approach, looking closely at social factors such as gender, race, ethnicity, class, sexuality, and gender identity, and analysing how they relate both to each other and to women's health. Connections between the social, economic, and cultural contexts of women's lives and their physical, spiritual, and mental well-being are a primary focus. Providing a much needed resource for teachers, students, and practitioners of women's health in Canada, this comprehensive volume makes an important contribution to the literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienexSociological aspects. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezCanada. 0aWomen's health serviceszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aApale, Alisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenoit, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Susan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowne, Annette J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Dena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiedrich, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoane, Gweneth Hartrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriesen, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankivsky, Olena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankivsky, Olena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMathieson, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrow, Marina , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorrow, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNahar, Kamrun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaimondo, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRicht